724799f-a.text:
110-114, 118 and 120 William Street (right to left) at, adioining and north of the N.E. corner of John Street. The 9-story structure (No. 120) appearing on the left, stands upon the former site of The Rigging House which was the first place fitted up for Methodist worship in New York. Services were held in this building between 1766-1788. For a lithograph
of same, see, D.T. Valentine's Manual.
About 1915.
Edwin Levick.

724796f-a.text:
(1)
William Street, west side, north from (No. 101) and including John Street, showing workmen constructing three additional stories to a 6story office building, Nos. 111-121 William Street, at the N.W. corner of John Street. On the opposite corner (S.W.) appears excavation for the foundation for the new 30-story New Amsterdam Casualty Building.
July 7, 1930.
P. L. Sperr.
(2)
A portion of the same, viewing slightly westward and showing a part of the John Street side of the building that is being enlarged. Adjoining it is the 16-story Travelers lInsurance Co. Building, No. 51-55 John Street, at the N.E. corner of Dutch Street. In the background is
visible the tower of the Woolworth Building.
July 7, 1930.
P. L. Sperr.
